You can dynamically request icon images from the Google charts api with the urls:
 http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chst=d_map_pin_letter&amp;chld=%E2%80%A2|FE7569
 Which looks like this:the image is 21√ó43 pixels and the pin tip is at position (10, 34)
And you‚Äôll also want a separate shadow image (so that it doesn‚Äôt overlap nearby icons):
 http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chst=d_map_pin_shadow
 Which looks like this:the image is 40√ó37 pixels and the pin tip is at position (12, 35)
When you construct your MarkerImages you need to set the size and achor points accordingly:
 var pinColor = ‚ÄúFE7569‚Äù;
var pinImage = new google.maps.MarkerImage(‚Äúhttp://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chst=d_map_pin_letter&amp;chld=%E2%80%A2|‚Äù + pinColor,
new google.maps.Size(21, 34),
new google.maps.Point(0,0),
new google.maps.Point(10, 34));
var pinShadow = new google.maps.MarkerImage(‚Äúhttp://chart.apis.google.com/chart?chst=d_map_pin_shadow‚Äù,
new google.maps.Size(40, 37),
new google.maps.Point(0, 0),
new google.maps.Point(12, 35));
 You can then add the marker to your map with:
 var marker = new google.maps.Marker({
position: new google.maps.LatLng(0,0),
map: map,
icon: pinImage,
shadow: pinShadow
});
 Simply replace ‚ÄúFE7569‚Äù with the color code you‚Äôre after. Eg:
